  "_comment": "slots are half-hour, 0 = midnight..0:30, 47 = 23:30..24:00. blocks are [start_slot, end_slot) with a place token — EXACTLY work|home|away|haunt:<place-id>; a bare place id throws, and Clockwork.ResolvePlace's catch-all silently sends a typo home. SLEEP IS A STRING MATCH: Clockwork sets asleep for any block whose activity contains 'asleep' (case-insensitive) — never use that word loosely. THE TWO NUMBERS THAT GOVERN THIS FILE (Pressures.cs, at 48 slots/day): 18 work slots = purse-neutral; 18 engaged slots (work OR haunt) = restlessness-neutral. Above/below 18 sets each drive's drift SIGN. Villagers sit above 18 engaged (they settle); adventurers sit at 8 (they get itchy and go to the board). That gradient is the design, not an accident — see scrap_scripts/design/new-town-design.md. BOTH 18s ARE THE UNTRAITED NUMBERS, and a purse/restlessness trait MOVES the townee's personal neutral — check it per-townee before trusting 18. TraitRateMod picks gain above the neutral and decay below it, so an asymmetric mod shifts where the sums cancel: `frugal {gain 1.0, decay 0.85}` slows only the idle half, so purse-neutral becomes 0.05W = (48-W)(0.03*0.85) => W = 16.2, NOT 18. Widow Karsk sat at exactly 16 work slots against her own 16.2 and drifted -0.0003/day — flat for life, against a design whose invariant is that no drive is flat for anyone. She is at 15 now (-0.0019/day); the freed slot went to her market-row haunt so her engaged count stays 32 and only purse moved.",
